<br>
No, that's not quite accurate. Nor even close to it.<br>
<br>
Here's what he said:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Well, anyway, I see this group (all from the same guild) come up and make camp in the middle of my pull through area.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If anything that's the opposite of being &quot;nowhere near them&quot;, because, quite simply, if he can see them, he must be at least relatively close to them <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Either way, the point you're trying to make, that he had &quot;left the camp&quot; for hours assumes an implicit premise: That camps are held by being in a specific spot - as opposed to killing specific mobs, and the process/geography through which it is performed.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>He trains them on purpose, as he admits<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes. But the method by which he trained them is what differentiates him from any random form of retribution. He trains them <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>by doing that which he had been doing for hours</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, namely pulling a swarm to kill it.<br>
<br>
To make this simpler: Had he pulled a swarm for purely kiting purposes, without the intent to kill the group, the result <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>would have been identical</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. The group would have died. What this reveals is that the group and he were in direct competition over a camp he had a rightful claim to. Not just that he trained them, he trained them because they relied on the following:<br>
<br>
If he tries to KS them, as a way to take back the camp, he'll fail miserably.<br>
<br>
If he tries to petition, the GM's will enforce a rotation, which ultimately will benefit them more than he.<br>
<br>
They tried to force his hand, so he played the cards he was dealt. They continued pulling to a location he had a legitimate claim to, and he continued his method of killing.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>He trains them again, as he admits<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You know, training in a duel is not in violation of the PnP *if* you get the killing blow.<br>
<br>
This would have worked had the group not interfered in the first place. (You can get a killing blow if only three mobs are hitting the enchanter - you can't if there's 20. Had the group not interfered, the enchanter would have been severely weakened by the 3 mobs, and the bard would have killed him/her.) Thus, the second train is a direct result of the actions of the group.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>He is a dumbfuck, as anyone who can follow the first 3 points can conclude.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, that conclusion is invalid. You have failed to provide the proof that if one trains repeatedly they are thereby a &quot;dumbfuck&quot; as you so blandly put it.<br>
<br>
Even so, your conclusion is also unsound. Quite simply, your premises are false.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>By the way, as a gently reminder, have a clue before you spew. Bullshit that is. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I will take your &quot;gently reminder&quot; under consideration. -chuckles- <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=iadas>Iadas</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>This is my title.<BR>
